      "symbolism": "Thebes symbolized the full flowering of Egyptian religious civilization. The city's division between east (living) and west (dead) embodied Egyptian cosmology - each day the sun rose over the temples of the living and set over the tombs of the dead, demonstrating the eternal cycle. Karnak, constantly expanding over millennia, represented the cumulative devotion of generations of pharaohs. The massive pylons and columns showed divine power made visible in stone. The Theban triad of Amun (father), Mut (mother), and Khonsu (son) represented the divine family and cosmic order. Thebes embodied Ma'at through its ordered architecture and rituals.",
      "culturalSignificance": "Thebes was Egypt's political and religious capital during the New Kingdom, the empire's golden age. The city's temples received enormous wealth from pharaohs returning from conquest. The Theban priesthood of Amun became so powerful that high priests eventually ruled Upper Egypt independently. Thebes produced some of history's most magnificent architecture - the Hypostyle Hall at Karnak, the mortuary temple of Hatshepsut, and tombs like Tutankhamun's. Later, foreign conquerors (Assyrians, Persians) sacked Thebes, symbolizing Egypt's decline. Today, the Theban monuments are among Egypt's greatest tourist attractions and represent ancient Egypt's architectural zenith."
